# .NET / C# Standards

Follow Microsoft's official coding conventions strictly.

## Naming
- PascalCase: classes, methods, properties, enums, interfaces (prefix I), events
- camelCase: local variables, method parameters
- _camelCase: private instance fields
- SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE: constants only if truly constant (prefer `static readonly`)

## Structure
- One class per .cs file; filename = class name
- Namespace must match folder structure
- Order members: fields → constructors → properties → public methods → private methods

## Code Style
- Use `var` only when the type is obvious
- Always use braces for control flow blocks
- Use expression-bodied members only for trivial one-liners
- Prefer `is null` over `== null`
- Use `string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace()` not `.Length == 0`
- Use `ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull()` (.NET 6+)

## Async
- All async methods must be named with Async suffix
- Always await — never use .Result, .Wait(), or .GetAwaiter().GetResult()
- Use CancellationToken parameters in all async methods

## Dapper / SQL
- Never build SQL strings via concatenation — use parameterized queries
- Map stored procedure results to strongly typed models
- Use `decimal` for all financial/monetary fields, never `double` or `float`

## API / Controllers
- Controllers must be thin — no business logic
- Use [FromBody], [FromQuery] attributes explicitly
- Return ActionResult<T> with appropriate HTTP status codes
- Use ProblemDetails for error responses